01:18:50.839 --> 01:19:05.839
But something that – it could be something that I have showed you, but you're like, wait a minute. What was that? That was way too fast, or I have no idea what was going on. Or it is something that I have not shown you.

01:19:05.839 --> 01:19:21.839
Maybe I'm just making all these assumptions in what is perhaps interesting or not interesting, but then I do hope that you'll be able to correct me. So, please, if you have any questions, now is the time.

01:19:21.839 --> 01:19:38.839
Although, if you have any questions after this tutorial, if you Google my name, you'll get to my website and you'll find various ways to get a hold of me. So, you're always welcome to shoot me a message.

01:19:38.839 --> 01:20:00.839
So, okay. So, Stephen mentions – oh, no, wait. Let's go back a little bit more. Risa Baltasar, does it do data visualizations as well, or is it better to use other packages for that? Okay. So, that's a yes and a no answer there, and a funny story.

01:20:00.839 --> 01:20:23.839
So, this was at a Christmas party maybe two years ago. Richie Vink, the creator of Polars, came up to me and said, hey, Jeroen, we're going to add visualization to Polars. And this was when I was like – we were like – we started writing the book and we already knew like this is going to take forever.

01:20:24.839 --> 01:20:39.839
And so, Richie said, okay, we're going to add even more functionality. And at first I was like, oh, man, there are already so many data visualization packages out there for Python. We don't need another data visualization package.

01:20:40.839 --> 01:20:58.839
But then, luckily, Richie was like, no, no, no, no, no. What we're going to do is we're going to – we're just going to add a plot namespace and then all the individual methods will be forwarded. They will use some other package under the hood.

01:20:59.839 --> 01:21:24.839
And when they first implemented this, this was a package called hvplot. So, and then I was like, all right, that's a solid choice. I'll start writing about this. Then once I was done with that chapter, they switched the backend thanks to Marco Gorelli, which at first I was, of course, really annoyed with Marco Gorelli.

01:21:25.839 --> 01:21:49.839
But we had a really good chat. We know each other by now. And I totally understood why they changed the backend to Altair. So, by itself, Polars – and by the way, the reason why I was annoyed is because I had to rewrite a good chunk of that data visualization chapter.

01:21:50.839 --> 01:22:05.839
But it's all good now. So, now the plotting backend is Altair. And so, Polars by itself doesn't do any data visualization. It has some methods that will then be forwarded to Altair.

01:22:06.839 --> 01:22:21.839
So, in my opinion, this is kind of limited. You can never have that same functionality as Altair itself. It's impossible to add that to Polars.

01:22:22.839 --> 01:22:39.839
So, I am personally inclined to just import explicitly some other data visualization package – could be Altair, could be Plot9, could be whatever – and then pass in the Polars data frame.

01:22:40.839 --> 01:22:55.839
Now, many visualization packages can work with Polars data frames, sometimes natively by using the NeuralWalls package under the hood, sometimes by first converting it to a Pandas data frame. It doesn't really matter in practice.

01:22:55.839 --> 01:23:13.839
So, that's the yes and the no. Let me see here.

01:23:13.839 --> 01:23:26.839
Let me read the questions. All right. Ola asks, Jeroen, what is your favorite thing about Polars? What would you say to convince someone to use it?

01:23:27.839 --> 01:23:47.839
So, that would be the API. It's not perfect, but I like it a lot more than the Pandas API. I don't want to hate on Pandas. We are all extremely grateful for Pandas. Without Pandas, there wouldn't be Polars.

01:23:48.839 --> 01:24:07.839
But I just find the way of writing Polars code to be more in line with how I think. Someone mentioned in the chat the tidyverse, and that is indeed something that I have used extensively over the years.

01:24:07.839 --> 01:24:26.839
And yeah, there are some similarities there as well. It's more about describing the operations that you want to do, and then let Polars figure out how to do that.

01:24:26.839 --> 01:24:54.839
Yeah, let me wrap up here. So, this was quite a crash course. I've been rambling a lot, and I can imagine that by now, I mean, if this was your first encounter with Polars, you feel pretty overwhelmed with everything that you have seen.

01:24:55.839 --> 01:25:13.839
That's okay. It's okay to be overwhelmed. What I do hope is that this has – that I have been able to give you enough so that you are inclined to try it out for yourself.

01:25:13.839 --> 01:25:30.839
And that's, of course, the best thing that you can do right now is to just get some data and install Polars using UV and just get going. Make mistakes. Just try things out. Read the documentation.

01:25:30.839 --> 01:25:49.839
Again, the book that we wrote, the first chapter you can get for free. That will allow you perhaps even better to determine whether you want to continue learning Polars. There is a learning curve involved.

01:25:49.839 --> 01:26:08.839
It also allows you to determine whether you think the book is worth your time and money. But I do hope – that's all I can hope for is that I have been able to inspire you a little bit when it comes to this wonderful package.

01:26:09.839 --> 01:26:21.839
So, thank you all so much for staying with me, and I wish you a wonderful time for the rest of the conference. Thanks.

01:26:21.839 --> 01:26:27.839
Thank you so much, Arun. I'm giving applause to you too from here.

01:26:27.839 --> 01:26:28.839
Thank you.

01:26:29.839 --> 01:26:46.839
We are out of time, so we're going to go ahead and wrap up this session. Thank you all for joining today. And if you'd like to continue this discussion, you can head over to the Discord. That link is available in the reception area. And a recording of this session will be available shortly.

01:26:46.839 --> 01:26:51.839
So, thank you guys so much, and I'm going to go ahead and end this session.

